Questions

Observations + Issues

This dataset describes loans made through the Lending Club platform. There are 10,000 rows each representing a loan. There are 55 columns describing each loan. At first glance, the dataset has many missing values. For example, in row 6, the emp_title is missing and theres an NA for emp_length. In the verified_income column, there is confusion since there is verified and source verified. It should just be a binary with verified or not verified. There are also several outliers that seem interesting. In num_historical_failed_to_pay, the mean is 0.1671 while the max is 52.

Visualizations

loans$paid_late_fees[loans$paid_late_fees==0] <- NA
exclude_late<- loans %>%
  drop_na(paid_late_fees)
ggplot(exclude_late, aes(x=paid_late_fees, y=total_credit_lines)) +
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("Total Credit Lines by Late Fees")

The plot is shows that theres no correlation between paid_late_fees and total_credit_lines. My speculation is that there would be a positive relationship between both since people with more credit lines would probably have more paid late fees since they have more credit lines to keep track of. However, this could be because the data had many 0 values for paid_late_fees and the sample size was reduced too much. I think it would be useful to have a late fees incurred dataset instead of paid late fees as the fees could be not paid. In addition, I am realizing now that the paid_late_fees referrs to paid late fees on the loan and not on the credit card. That explains why there is no correlation.

Interest Rate Prediction

The first model I am creating is very simple and uses the elements Ive been investigating prior. I am first making a linear regression model with annual income + total debit limit as the independent variables and interest rate as the dependent variable.

reg<- lm(interest_rate ~ annual_income + total_debit_limit, data = loans)
summary(reg)

To better visualize this output and analyze its meanings, I will first create a histogram to visualize the residuals

ggplot(data = loans, aes(reg$residuals)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black", fill = "blue") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
        axis.line.x = element_line(),
        axis.line.y = element_line()) +
  ggtitle("Histogram for Regression Model Residuals")

The goal of the histogram is to see if the data is normal around 0. Since its not and slightly right skewed, it exemplifies that the model does not fit the data too well. Perhaps the variables I chose were not correlated enough. In addition, the R squared shows that its not a well-fitted model since its very far away from 1. To confirm, I am making one more visualization to check for model fitness.

ggplot(data = loans, aes(x = total_debit_limit + annual_income, y = interest_rate)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", col="dodgerblue") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
        axis.line.x = element_line(),
        axis.line.y = element_line()) +
  ggtitle("Linear Model Fitted")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

As one can see, this graph represents the inaccuracy and un-usability of my model.
